  "prompt": "Is it the Big Ongoing, not the Big Bang?",
  "response": "The phrase \"Big Ongoing\" is not a recognized scientific term in cosmology. The widely accepted model for the origin of the universe is the \"Big Bang,\" which describes the expansion of the universe from a hot, dense initial state. This event occurred approximately 13.8 billion years ago and marks the beginning of time and space as we understand them.\n\nHowever, there are ongoing theories and discussions in cosmology about what occurs after the Big Bang, what might have preceded it, and the nature of the universe's future. Concepts such as cosmic inflation, dark energy, and the eventual fate of the universe (e.g., Big Crunch, Big Freeze) represent some of these ongoing investigations into the universe's evolution.\n\nIf you meant something else by \"Big Ongoing,\" please clarify, and I'd be happy to provide more information!",
